Good evening.
Seventy percent of our planet is covered with oceans, and yet, strangely, we have decided to call it "Earth".
The poet Heathcote Williams shared a more objective and less anthropocentric view, when he said that "seen from space, the planet is blue.
From space, the planet is the territory not of humans, but of whales."
Yet, we all come from the ocean.
It is the cradle of life, even if we forgot it.
Ocean is everywhere: in glaciers, rivers, water tables, in the cells of living beings, and in our veins.
Strangely, it's John Fitzgerald Kennedy who has best illustrated it in this quote: "It's an interesting biological fact that all of us have, in our veins, the exact same percentage of salt in our blood that exists in the oceans.
Therefore, we all have salt in our blood, in our sweat, in our tears.
We are tied to the ocean, and when we go back to the sea whether to sail on it or to look at it, we are going back from whence we came."
Nevertheless, our knowledge of this ocean is very limited.
It remains a somewhat strange and alien world, that sometimes scares us.
That said, in truth, it is far from being an inert body of water, an expanse of water that serves no purpose.
In fact, it is marine life that makes our oceans one of the main regulator of the climate, the main carbon sink, and also the main supplier of oxygen.
Between 50% and 70% of oxygen comes from the ocean.
So in reality, more than one inhale in two, that you take, you owe it to the ocean -
not exactly to the ocean
but rather to marine life.
It is marine life that actually enables this body of water to be not just an inert body of water but the machinery that allows us to live.
Marine life starts with phytoplankton which produce oxygen, and end with big whales including large predators, tuna and dolphins ... And among those species, some are ecologically more important than others, especially sharks.
This is, therefore, the example I've chosen because it is an animal that we tend to demonize, a sea monster.
Yet, 70 million sharks are slaughtered each year.
That's exterminating a population equivalent to that of France.
But sharks are record-holders in evolution.
They are 470 million years old.
Concretely what it means is that, for 470 million years, all life in the ocean was shaped by and depending on sharks.
As a top predator, a keystone species, when you remove sharks from an ecosystem, the result is a collapse of marine biodiversity.
So where sharks have disappeared, waters are dead, or there's an explosion of jellyfish, but there is no life.
So there you have it.
That's the role of predators.
We, as humans, tend to think that we are the top predators.
However, we are far from being predators since, in Nature, predators are, on one hand, regulated by the availability of their preys - and that's no longer true for us since we invented agriculture and farming - and, on the other hand, predators tend to reproduce less.
Thus, cheetahs or lions tend to have far fewer young than mice or rabbits.
In Nature, mice and rabbits are prey, of course, so they need to reproduce rapidly and in large numbers.
Sharks, whales, and dolphins are predators.
They have not been designed to be prey.
We have made them preys !
So they cannot survive the predatory pressure of man.
There is also a common attribute held by all these marine animals, whether they are predators or not:
they all take part in marine life - that is, in a cycle essential to life - while we do not.
To give you an example, one blue whale produces three tonnes of excrement a day - excrements that are rich in nitrogen or azote - that are vital nutrients for phytoplankton which provides us with the oxygen we breathe.
So we have lost 40% of the phytoplankton population over the last 50 years, largely because of the extermination of whales in the 20th century and before, but above all, since the invention of the explosive harpoon.
A human goes to sea,
but he isn't part of this ecosystem.
We are no longer part of it since we have left the ocean.
So, we are an intruder.
We are an intruder with means of fishing, of predation, that are today industrialized.
So we're a predator who no longer has the natural boundaries of predators.
So, there is more than 7 billion of us, and today, 7 billion human beings want to eat fish.
That's a big problem indeed.
The other problem is this illusion we've had for a long time and may still have today, although to a lesser extent, that sealife is limitless.
Jules Michelet, who wrote a fairly well known book which is a reference work on the subject, illustrates it rather well: "In some narrow passages, we cannot row, the sea is solid.
Millions of millions, billions of billions, who would dare risk a guess at the number of these legions?
It's said that once, near Le Havre, just one fisherman found 800,000 of them.
In a Scottish port, 11,000 barrels of them were produced in one night."
When we read historic testimonies, we are told that, off the western Atlantic coast of France, we could see whales passing by for days, and boats needed to heave for days.
Those living near the coast couldn't sleep sometimes, so loud was the sound of the whales' blows.
Today, we are amazed when we see a fin.
We have lost the memory of what the sea once was before we started fishing.
Here is a quote from Thomas Huxley that illustrates well the lack of knowledge and the state of denial we were in: "Nothing we do can affect the number of fish."
Yet today, we have already exterminated 90% of the oceans' large fish.
The problem also is that we have a hard time feeling empathy for fish.
It is difficult to save the whales.
Whales are charismatic animals that could greatly attract sympathy.
Yet today, in 2016, they continue to die from the blows of explosive harpoons, despite moratoria, despite sanctuaries.
This is also one of the major fights of Sea Shepherd because we think that if we cannot save the whales, saving anything else in the ocean is going to be very complicated, let alone the sharks, which are regarded as monsters, or the tuna in which we show little interest.
Fish are so disregarded that we refer to them in terms of tonnes.
So you will hear about 14,000 tons of quotas: 14,000 tons of tuna, or 16,000 tons of shark.
You'd be shocked if I were to talk about tons of giraffes or tons of dogs ... or tons of French people!
Fish are not even regarded as individuals.
It's just a mass that's part of a stock that might be protected if necessary, in order to get maximum returns from its exploitation in a sustainable way.
So, we can also tell ourselves
that, in the end, if fish are disappearing, if the ocean is in trouble,
it doesn't matter since we're doing well.
We are numerous, we are everywhere.
Nevertheless, we need to be careful because some signs may be misguiding.
In reality, a number of factors precedes the extinction of a species. The main ones are the following three: Demographic explosion, the overexploitation of resources, and occupying all ecological niches, meaning spreading out everywhere.
Maybe that reminds you of someone ...
If you are looking for an example of an endangered species, there's no need to search on Google, just look at yourself in a mirror or look at your neighbor.
So, we are not doing so well.
Today we are told about sustainable fishing.
Yet the scientists of the United Nations are expecting a fishery collapse by 2048.
2048 is in 32 years, so, it's ... tomorrow morning.
What does "fishery collapse" means in real life?
It means no more fish.
It does't mean solely that fish will be off the menu or that when you'll go to the fishmonger's, it will be empty, it means the death of the ocean.
Because as I explained earlier, prior to being a food source, fish, just as marine life, are the essential work force that allows the ocean to be precisely that extraordinary machinery enabling us to stay alive.
Imagine having to go without more than one breath in two.
Imagine that all the carbon dioxide captured by the ocean - which is even more than that captured by forests - was found in the atmosphere.
The fact is, it would be the end of human civilization.
So...
Basically, I have given you motives, I've given you very down-to-earth motives, we might say, why we should protect the ocean.
Ultimately, the solution is quite simple, for us, for everyone.
If you are not strictly dependent on fish to live, the best thing to do is to stop eating it.
Seven billion human beings will never be able to eat fish.
We would exterminate marine life.
Well, that's when we think from an utilitarian perspective because the leitmotiv is this: if the ocean dies, we will die.
So, if we'd like to stay alive and want our children to stay alive after us, we need to take drastic action to change our lifestyles and adapt.
And that's the keyword of evolution and for species that want to survive.
As Darwin told us, we should adapt or perish.
So we need to adapt and to adapt quickly.
But, on a personal level, what motivates me in all of this, which is why I'm here in front of you this evening, it's not so much the question, utilitarianist, of survival, commendable, but utilitarianist.
In fact, it's rather ... this difficulty that I have of living with this injustice in the way we treat all that is weaker than us - and I find that this is, morally and ethically, the driving force that propels me - an injustice very well described by Milan Kundera, in this extract from his book "The Unbearable Lightness of Being": "Man's true goodness can manifest itself with complete purity and complete freedom, only with respect to those of no strength.
Humanity's true moral test, and its most radical - which lies at a level so deep that it goes unnoticed - is its relationships with those who are at its mercy: animals.
And here occurred man's fundamental failure, so fundamental that all other failures ensue it ..." Thank you.
(Applause)
My daily life is made up of feelings that most of you know nothing about.
For a long time, I was ashamed of it.
I remember very well the circumstances in which I discovered this difference.
I was four years old and wanted to express to my mother the joy I felt watching the sun through a leaf and I told her not about the leaf itself, but the colors and sensations that were caused by what I felt when I saw that leaf: these yellow and green lines, this very special taste, halfway between sugar, mint, cucumber, that came to me following the ribs and imagining a whole series of possible futures, imagination, like a golden mist, joy like shimmering water ... She just thought I was crazy.
And then, so, I hid it, and growing up, I was frustrated to keep these perceptions that seem very beautiful for me and I tried to represent them in this painting that you see.
Immediately, thinking about these emotions, I also found those I had felt listening to this music, Verdi's Va Pensiero.
(Music) Synesthesia is not a disease, it's just a different perception of things which leads senses that normally are not interconnected to connect.
For example, you hear the E note, and you see it blue or green.
You taste an apple and the taste of this apple will evoke a geometric form.
It's innate and it's involuntary.
There is a multitude of different synesthesia, according to debated evaluations, it affects about one out of 2,000 people; debated because most synesthetes do not know they are synesthete until they discover the existence of the phenomenon.
Thanks to my synesthesia, my emotions, my thoughts, my associations of ideas, as you could see, my little inner voice, everything appears to me in the form of colors, shapes, tastes, movements.
It enriches my perception of the world and the paintings I'm trying to make to represent all of this are about as faithful to the original perception than a freeze frame compared to a three-hour film or a photo of chocolate cake versus a real chocolate cake.
But it's still a lot more revealing than words.
Words do not say anything about the world and that's what I tried to paint in this painting: down on the left, you have the reality, the emotions it inspires me, the thoughts, above, the imaginary; at the crossroads of the imaginary and reality, the voice.
And little by little, you have this narrowing by going to the right, when it is necessary to convey all this inner wealth in this tiny dead end that the words are.
Throughout my childhood, I have wondered why we had not invented specific words to say all this wealth.
Why we did not invent a specific word to talk about the joy we experience when we look at the sunlight through a leaf?
Why we did not invent another different word to express the joy we experience when we see one's child again, when we see one's spouse?
It has nothing in common, however.
Probably because it was not deemed useful and in fact, recent research on synesthesia would tend to show that we would all, as children, have these extra nerve connections, explaining synesthesia.
But we lose them little by little.
There is no inevitability to that, the words are a frame, a convention allowing us to communicate, now, nothing forbids us to preserve the richness of our perception.
Yet we do not do it, we enclose ourselves within the frame of words, we shrink our perception of the world to these words while nothing obliges us to, probably because we think that's what others expect of us.
In ancient times, studies carried out on ancient languages showed that the colors were perceived in a very particular order: first black, white, red, green or yellow, and finally blue.
So this sea you see blue, ancient Greeks saw it as purple, for example.
Conversely, where you see snow, a Scotsman will be able to think of one of the 421 words used in his language to talk about snow.
Of course, it has an impact on the way you see the world, you perceive it, it is probably this change of scenery that we seek by going to the other end of the planet to discover new landscapes, certainly, but also new ways of seeing, of perceiving.
And very oddly, no one makes this trip that can be just as fascinating, which is simply asking your neighbor: "Your perception of the world, your little inner voice, what does it say to you?"
If I make you travel in my synesthesia, you will enter a world where to use the same word remains the best guarantee not to understand each other.
When I worked in financial diplomacy about 13 to 14 years ago, there was a very fashionable term, it was "sound policies", which was used to designate the policies what a country should set up to receive assistance or debt reduction.
In the UN vision, "sound policies" it was a global respect for human rights and not too much corruption.
For the IMF, it was balanced budget, period.
For the World Bank, it's the UN's vision, that of the IMF, and then other things, investments in economic development, agriculture, urbanization, transport.
Now, these three international organizations, you put them at the same table, on the same text, using that same word, visually, you see right away that misunderstandings will be numerous.
You may be able to grasp the beauty of diplomatic language which consists in giving the illusion of an agreement when one is not necessary to move forward, but you will also understand why there is need then of a whole bureaucracy to handle what happens next.
To enter my synesthesia is also to understand an environment where thoughts and emotions appear at the same time like a satellite map and at the microscopic level.
I represented in this picture the vision that comes to me when I think, in a novel that I'm writing, at the meeting between the main character, Arthur, and his friend Bérénice, at a point when Berenice got injured, the way they will fall in love and lose sight of each other.
Behind this overall vision, you have lots more microscopic visions which correspond to the chapter details, to the characters' personality elements.
For example, the table on your left designates and illustrates how Arthur sees Berenice's character.
A cheerful girl who is hopeful but also presents dark incomprehensible ideas.
If I vary the circumstances of their meeting, if they meet at the beach, if Arthur's character is different, if Berenice loses her dark ideas, immediately, the vision I'm going to have of the chapter will change, both at the satellite level and at the microscope level.
You're probably wondering what it's like to be synesthetic?
This is a difficult question as it is something that you don't control, that you're born with.
But we can play and have fun with it.
Personally, I think it's a great wealth to always be at the border between two frames: the synesthetic one in which I think and the words I'm trying to communicate with today.
To play with the frames, that means for example not to brainstorm at the word level but at the level of perceptions and sensations that precede these words.
I'm willing to bet that the creators of Cleopatra glue, which some of you here may remember, thought a lot more about the almond smell of this glue than its glue properties as such.
To play with frames is also not to feel compelled by the way others will receive your message.
So, I wanted to write a poem and to make a painting that illustrated the synesthetic vision which gave rise to this poem.
I told a publisher who told me that he was not interested, that what mattered was the text, the painting was irrelevant.
I talked to a gallerist who had the opposite reaction: the painting is the most important, the text is irrelevant.
And then, after a first moment of discouragement, I thought the most important was the message: what was the form, what was the mode of expression, adequate for this message?
So, if I try to make a poem to express the emotion that my synesthesia gives me on a daily basis, it could look like this: the fire dismasted in the fury of sounds, pitched up like a sun, the almond of reality with orphan constellations dazzles the thought between non-existent vertigoes.
This is the poem that corresponds to the picture you have in front of you.
For me, both are linked and inseparable.
Now, poetry lovers will be more sensitive to poems or not, painting enthusiasts will be more sensitive to painting or not, but ultimately, it does not matter, because here stops the adventure of my perception and yours begins.
(Applause)
Hello.
Do you know what I do every day while walking around Paris?
I can't help myself.
I open the trash cans, and I look at what's inside.
At first, my kids were ashamed.
Now, I'm very happy because they do the same.
So, every day I pull out bottles, containers, cans, and a lot of cardboard from the trash can.
These materials are recyclable.
They should not be
in the trash; not at all.
And yet, here they are.
It takes three seconds to sort out.
One, two, three. Three seconds.
That's not long, and yet,
if multiplied by 65 million residents each day,
it is huge for the environment. Huge.
So when do we need these three seconds?
We need them after lunch.
We need them after dinner.
We need them when we get rid of something. We ask ourselves, "Do I throw it away or do I sort?"
Do I lose or do I win?
So, what do we lose and what do we win?
We lose a lot - we all do - if we don't sort.
Because these recyclable materials are wasted.
They will be burned, or buried in landfills.
And we are not told the following: when they are in landfills, there is a little bit that will end up in the forests, in the countryside, and in the sea.
If we all sort, we win tremendously.
Tremendously.
A can that is sorted will first be transported, sorted, gathered, transformed, treated and then become a can again, or maybe a bicycle, a car, all kind of objects.
And it's the same thing with glass, it's the same thing with plastic and bottles, and it's the same thing with cardboard.
All these materials can - if put in the correct receptacle - be reused.
Everyone of us can sort, everyone can, downstairs from us
or next to us; everyone.
And it takes three seconds.
This capacity to sort, this capacity not to pollute is simple.
And we owe it to two men.
Two men who, in the 90s, changed everything.
Remember back then the time of landfills.
They were everywhere, they were increasing, and we couldn't handle the environmental impact of consumption.
And then these two men decided to trust each other
instead of going for the typical response of, "Let's introduce a tax."
And then we create an administration. There will be an administration that looks after it.
And then the subject is forgotten.
No, these two men, Brice Lalonde, Minister for Ecology in 1992, and Antione Riboud, boss of Danone, decide to do something different.
Whereas few people talked about ecology in 1992, they said, "There you go, we are going to build a private business. A company without a lucrative aim, but it will be private.
And it will serve 100% to the public interest.
100% private, 100% dedicated to the public interest, to concentrate on that subject.
So it will take on, and it will be sure to attract the other companies."
50, 000 other big consumption companies have united, and they have worked with local communities.
An incredible invention. And then the public indeed was to do the collecting, the sorting, and the recycling.
The private company "Éco-Emballages" would be the one to pilot the operation and the state would control them and specify targets.
At this time, this creates a dynamic.
Companies, brands, associations, local communities, municipality, waste operators, and recyclers, while having all a completely different attitude, unite and tell themselves, "Come on, we'll get there!"
And the yellow recycling bin gets installed everywhere - or pretty everywhere - and the sorting begins.
Today, we have an extremely performant system.
In fact, the company "Éco-Emballages" works in a simple way.
A company that sells a packed product will pay a lot if the packing is heavy.
If the packing is light, eco-designed, it will pay less.
Afterwards, "Éco-Emballages" finances the whole thing.
Each year, 650 million euros are invested in sorting, gathering, and recycling.
So today, I'm also here to tell you that we have some difficulties.
In fact, for some years, the collecting hasn't progressed anymore.
It is stable.
And there are two issues
I want to talk about. The first one is the city.
In the city, half the amount of the countryside's gets recycled.
Only 30% is recycled in the city.
That means in this room is only one person out of three that sorts.
And bad news: In some years, in less than ten years, 85% of the people will live in cities.
The second issue is the plastic.
In 1950, we produced 1,5 million tons of plastic.
Today we produce 350 million.
In some time, we will produce 750 million tons of plastic.
And the problem is that only 23% of plastic is recyclable.
If we don't sort the plastic, it will become this.
We need to sort the plastic because the seventh continent does exist.
The seventh continent is in the sea, made of plastic particles that flow slowly, and will create the biggest garbage dump in the world.
There is an alternative to this.
If we ever do this: If we ever take this bottle and all the rest, and if we put it in this bin, and if we use it, what happens next?
This happens:
this is plastic that can be used to reproduce a bottle.
This is plastic made without petroleum, this is plastic that is reusable for all kind of objects, that we can use every day without touching natural resources.
This is plastic that derives from the yellow bin.
This is plastic that derives from your sorting.
And that is why today I launch an appeal for ideas, an appeal for projects.
Among yourselves, with your friends, your associations, in the quarters, try to find some projects, some ideas that re-launch the collecting, that allow us to produce this, that allow us to transform the plastic in resources.
And a resource has some value.
If a family doesn't sort today, it is like throwing away 30 euros in the bin each year.
You will tell me, "30 euros; that's not much."
But if you take 200 apartments that do the same thing in a building, that makes 6,000 euros.
In a city or a neighborhood of 30,000 inhabitants, that's 900,000 euros being thrown away each year.
That is why I launch this appeal for projects.
Organize yourselves, send us your proposals.
Together with local communities, we will find solutions to select them, to finance them.
Today I wanted to tell you that our only competitor is inaction, and that it takes three seconds, three seconds to prevent pollution. It's simple, and it's tremendous.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Good evening everyone.
I am going to tell you my story.
I am 17 years old and just obtain my baccalaureate.
My father only dreams of one thing: that I prepare for the entrance exams to the "grandes écoles."
He himself teaches at the ESCP computer science and marketing.
So he tells me, "Go for it my son, hang in there!
Surpass yourself!"
Me, personally, I only think of one thing actually: mainly, going beyond the confines of my neighborhood.
I can only think of one thing: to leave and travel far in France but also elsewhere.
So, I modestly enrolled at Nanterre University in ethnology and then in ethno-musicology.

Ah! Here is a good opportunity to travel.
I work on my thesis about the music of Benin, of North Benin, a population called the Nyende ...
Two months travelling, four months travelling.
But alas, I find it difficult to finish university.
I only think of one thing and it is playing music.
I am a drummer, a percussionist.
I work with different world music ensembles.
I love all types of music: biguine, jazz, African music, Balkan music, Raï, and so on.
In 2004, I founded my own band called Haïdouti Orkestar.
What is Haïdouti Orkestar?
It’s a combination of Balkan, Oriental and Turkish music.
Quite a variety!
Does this ring any bells?
Does this speak to you?
Not really.
This group consists of musicians from very, very different backgrounds.
As Georges Moustaki would say, a true bunch of wops.
We have a Greek from Rue de la Roquette who can hardly string together three words of Greek; a genuine gypsy from Serbia; a Bulgarian; some French people - yes, French people like me, but upon scratching the surface, not really truly French - a Spanish woman who claims she is Catalan, if you please, from Barcelona.
Do you know this group Haïdouti Orkestar?
No.
Yes, I heard a yes. There’s one person.
So much the better, here’s a clip.
(Video) (Song: "Ya Ayn Moulayiitain") (Sylvain on stage) This song is a tribute to Syria, to the Arab Spring, at a time in which there still remains a bit of hope.
Usually in concerts, the audience gets up and starts to dance.
You can ... It feels good too!
(Rhythmic claps) (End of video) (Applause) Thank you.
I discovered this music at the end of the 1980's - it’s getting a bit old - especially through Emir Kusturica’s films "le Temps des gitans," "Underground."
I’m sure everyone know those films.
Yes, of course.
For me, it was love at first sight, an amazing realization.
I developed a passion for these musics.
I literally fell in love with them, and I delved deeper.
It was the start of a long immersion into these cultures.
On this journey, I was to meet people, musicians, because for me, it was about immersing myself in the world of Balkan music, the Gypsy music, I didn’t know anybody, and about encountering Turkish music, all that stuff.
And that’s just what I did.
I am going to dwell for a moment on three people very important to me.
Firstly, Jasko Ramic.
Behind him is a woman playing the tuba.
She is the only woman in the band.
I think a lot about her, her name is Charlotte.
Back to Mr Jasko Ramic.
He is a gypsy from Serbia.
He is a true accordion virtuoso, a real "big shot" as we say.
He has an empirical and theoretical knowledge of all these musics.
I meet him in a basement bar in Paris.
A Bulgarian musician friend introduces him to me.
In addition, he is a polyglot.
He speaks Russian.
He speaks the Romany and Serbo-Croatian languages.
But as for me, I come and I speak French,
and I can't communicate with him.
Big problem. How can we break this barrier?
In the end, we don’t talk, we play.
Since then, we’ve been working together for more than 10 years.
He helps me to discover this culture, this music, its energy, its nostalgia.
And personally, I see that what I learn contrasts greatly with what I hear in the media.
What do I hear of the Roma people in the media?
I hear things that are not very nice.
They speak of shanty towns, of child abduction.
But I experience something completely different.
I travel in Bulgaria, in Macedonia. in Greece.
I feel safe there.
I meet with generous people who have literally given me their music.
There you have it.
I advise you to check out the work of "La Voix des Rroms," an association that deals with the Romany community's issues and aims to promote a more positive image.
The second person who has been very important to me is a trumpeter.
He is Lebanese but above all French since he grew up a few kilometres from here in the south of the region.
This guy has an incredible energy.
I met him when he was 25,
it's now a good 10 years.
He is Lebanese, and his parents fled Lebanon.
That’s important.
Today, this guy is well known.
His name is Mr Ibrahim Maalouf.
I’m sure you’ve heard of him.
This guy brings us to the Olympia.
Recently, we wrote the music for Mohamed Hamidi’s film "La Vache," starring Djamel Wilson ... Djamel Debbouze, Lambert Wilson!
(Laughter) (Video: Music "Le grand voyage") That’s the meeting of cultures!
Here’s a clip.
(Sylvain on stage) That's the instrument I play, among others. I play the drums. (Video: Ibrahim Maalouf
and Haïdouti Orkestar – "Le grand voyage")
(End of video) (Applause) The third person who has been very important to me in my career, on my journey, is Mr Zéki Çölaş. This man hails all the way from Antioch in Turkey,
at 80 km from Syria.
He fled Turkey at the age of 30 for political reasons, a saz under his arm.
He traveled through Syria. spent some time in Germany, and ended up in France, in Bobigny.
So I meet this gentleman in a restaurant in Paris, a good fifteen years ago. I can’t remember if it was a Kurdish or Turkish restaurant.
For me, back then, they were kind of the same thing.
But in reality, they are very different.
I end up taking a walk with this man.
He shows me Little Istanbul.
Do you know Little Istanbul?
Little Istanbul is the Turkish quarter in Paris between Château d'Eau and Strasbourg Saint-Denis.
It’s here that this culture, this community comes together.
So we walk through the streets.
We meet his friends from the Özgül book store.
We go to listen to the latest arrivals at Tuana Music, the only Turkish music shop in Paris.
All the novelties, records, musical instruments and so on, everything related to Turkey is found there.
Very quickly, we grow a desire to share things, to familiarize ourselves with this Turkish music which we don't know and which is largely unknown in France.
We also decide to go further and open ourselves up to other cultures.
Here we are, I had another map earlier.
This is not the same one.
Anyway, we are also interested in Armenia and Azerbaijan.
We try to go beyond our limits, to cross the borders.
You’ll notice that this whole region is today a real powder keg, between the migrant problem, the Kurdish issue, and Erdogan who has now become a true dictator - we can say this plainly.
So, it’s at this point that certain associations made contact with us, associations that have values somehow similar to ours, that are in favor of sharing.
I am thinking about La Cimade, Valeur ajoutée.
I met La Cimade in Massy, not too far from here.
Each year, they throw a party, where there is a lot to eat, different dishes from all countries.
That was another moment of sharing.
I am also thinking about BAAM, the Migrant Reception and Support Office.
Last September, we held a concert.
This was equally a huge moment of emotion and sharing.
Somalian, Erythrean, Turkish, French people, everyone gathered to unite through our music.
It was a tremendous moment.
More recently, I also wanted to go beyond genres, so I set out to find the jazz music.
(Video: Haïdouti Orkestar and Bojan Z- Tchagri) (Sylvain on stage) Here is a Bosnian pianist.
With this presentation, I wanted to show you how much music and my encounters and that cross-breeding is a means to open us up to the world.
There you have it.
Thank you.
(Applause)
It's early in the morning.
You're looking at yourself in the mirror.
What do you say?
Not so long ago, I would say to myself,
"Hey! Hello handsome."
(Laughter) But more recently, it came as a shock, when I found myself saying, "My goodness ..." "I look like my grandpa!"
Perhaps you like what you see in the mirror.
Or perhaps not ...
In any case, you will recognize the reflection as your own.
How do you recognize yourself?
What constitutes your identity?
This is a crucial question, because the way in which we define ourselves alters the way in which we relate to others.
In the past, I believed that I had a concrete identity:
I was a Mexican ready to conquer the world.
So I started by moving to Paris.
Eleven years ago.
And everything went proceeding as planned, until last year.
Indeed, three events led me to question myself, "Who is this person that I call me?"
"Hello!
Have we met?"
The first event, I call it, "Meeting the ancestors".
One day, while I was surfing the Internet, I read an article which said, "If your surname is on this list, you may be a descendent of one of the Sephardic Jewish families expelled from Spain in the 15th century."
And perhaps soon you may be able to request Spanish nationality.
I consulted the list.
To my great surprise, my father's surname Meza was on the list.
As a Mexican, I expected to have a little Spanish blood in my veins.
But I had never imagined this. Does this mean that a little Jewish blood flows in my Mexican veins?
Is this the reason that I enjoyed so much the movie "Fiddler on the Roof"?
Or more importantly: does this mean that I now have the right to put guacamole in my falafel?
(Laughter) It might be mad, but ever since I read that article, I feel closer to my Jewish side.
The second event: "A beginner's lesson in cellular identity". There I am, conversing with my friend, Julien, a French biologist by profession.
He explained the following to me, "Antonio, from the biological point of view, I can tell you that this question about your identity is meaningless.
Let me explain: your cells reproduce and die, agreed?
And your body takes seven years to regenerate entirely.
So you could say that after seven years, you are an entirely different person to the one you were before."
"Hang on!" I say; you know
that I've lived in France for 11 years.
And you're telling me that since then, the cells of my body have been regenerating with proteins coming directly from Camembert,
from Cassoulet,
and from Confit de Canard?
(Laughter) Does that mean that, from a biological point of view, I am already French?"
(Laughter) It might be mad to say but, since that conversation with Julien, I feel closer to my French side.
And finally, the third event,
"The ring on the finger moment". Yes, last year, I got married.
Thank you, thank you.
(Applause) And my lovely wife is German.
(Laughter) Well, her mother is German, and her father is Hungarian.
So she's half German, half Hungarian.
It might be mad, but, since I got married, I feel much closer to my new German and Hungarian sides.
It's like an entirely new family.
But, can you imagine the day, that we have a child?
How would we explain their background?
"My son, my daughter, your Mexican heritage signifies that you have Spanish and Aztec origins.
But also Jewish roots.
Morever, you have a German trunk and Hungarian branches.
And you grew on French soil.
That makes you quite an exotic plant.
(Laughter) I think my children are going to need at least four passports.
Not to mention some good counseling.
Following these three events, I was completely lost.
Who are my people?
Will I have to renounce the person I am in order to embrace the one I will become?
Who is this person that I call "me"?
All things considered, it was me who needed some good counseling.
But a few weeks later, I took a course of personal development given by my friend Robert from California.
During the seminar, Robert gave us the following exercise. You are face-to-face with another person, and looking at them, you say,
"I see you. I can see your strength.
And I can see your fragility.
And I know that you are much more than this."
When Robert explained this exercise, I really thought that it was Californian hippy madness.
(Laughter) And yet, when my partner in this exercise spoke those words to me, this might seem crazy, but I felt much closer to myself.
At last, I had no need to know in my head who I was, I could quite simply recognise myself in the gaze of the other.
Their eyes became the mirror where I could recognize myself, I saw my origins, and my potential.
I could embrace the whole.
I could be so much more than I had imagined. And it feels good.
It's early in the morning, you're looking at yourself in the mirror.
What do you say?
You are so much more than the color of your skin, so much more than the borders of your country, and much more than your genetic heritage.
So, tomorrow morning, when you go to look at yourself in the mirror, try saying this to yourself,
"Hello! I see you.
And I can see your strength.
And I can see your fragility.
And I know that you are much more, much more than all of that."
Thank you.
(Applause)
Can you imagine hospital patients having to wait weeks for treatment?
Last year, a hospital called me to coach a unit that was on the point of closing,
and that was going to jeopardize part of this hospital's organization.
Doctors were resigning one after the other, and the administrative and nursing staff were completely demotivated.
And having analysed it, it turned out that it was all linked to the style of leadership of the department head - let's call him Doctor X.
This Doctor X is somebody who is very authoritarian, very controlling, and is not a very good communicator.
And yet, he is a world authority in his field of expertise.
As patients, you, just like me, want to be cared for by these demi-gods on Earth, but if he isn't capable of keeping his team, the chances are high that his expertise will disappear with him, and that he won't be able to treat as many patients as he does today.
Being an excellent doctor doesn't make him an excellent manager.
And headhunters understood this very well.
I am Marie-Bernard Guillaume, and I'm going to explain to you tonight why, from a headhunter, I became a heart hunter.
Most of the business leaders that I meet share the same concern: how to motivate their staff?
Do you know that according to Gallup surveys, only one in ten employees is really happy and enthusastic at work.
Seven out of ten do their job but you can't expect more from them.
Two out of ten are even active saboteurs: they turn up at work with their unhappiness, and they prevent others from functioning properly.
Imagine the resulting catastrophe if we were to apply this ratio to our national football team. (Laughter)
I see you're starting to feel the pain, you understand the issue for managers.
How can an employee be motivated?
Have you all heard of Maslow's Pyramid?
Well, forget it!
(Laughter) Other studies have shown that we all share three needs, three motivating factors that are universal whether you're a man or a woman, young or old.
Regardless of our philosophical or religious beliefs, we all share these factors and these needs.
The first need is the need for personal development.
It's being able to use my skills to follow my dreams, to achieve my goals, so I could say,
"Wow, I'm good! I've done it!
I'm proud of myself."
The second is the need for autonomy.
It's being able to do what I want, when I want, and how I want.
The third is the need for connectivity.
It's being able to feel that you belong and have links to a community, to a team, to a family.
It's being supported, being "liked" on Facebook.
So, as you'll have understood, the company who is able to meet those three factors is likely to see a much higher rate of commitment from its employees than elsewhere.
Yet, most managers today still function like our Doctor X, with a well defined hierarchical pyramid, and roles and duties that cover everybody's function, such that it is suffocating and killing any need for autonomy and all initiative.
Luckily, luckily, more and more companies have understood this problem and are setting up leadership cultures that are participatory, collaborative.
In these companies, the well-being of the employee comes first, success and financial results come as a consequence,
and not the other way round.
The hierarchical pyramid is also switched to replace managers with teams who take decisions together, collectively.
It's not cloud-cuckoo land, so obviously, there are results to achieve and goals. But above all, there is a vision and values that are shared by everybody.
Each person is driving his or her own work.
I could quote several examples of success.
I'm going to talk about a company that you have certainly heard of, given the average age here. I mean Netflix, the company in the Silicon Valley.
They've decided to set up an HR culture in which responsibility and freedom
are the words of the day. Imagine: you are free to organize your work however you want, and wherever you want; your expenses are not checked; the number of day's leave you take is not controlled; all that is asked of you is to act in the company's best interests.
Is this not a perfect answer to empowering employees?
You're also asked to take initiatives and mistakes are accepted, because you can't have one without the other.
This is what creates a movement of innovation and intrapreneurship within the company.
I could quote other examples of success, but let's focus on the people who make these changes, who are they?
Obviously, they are the business leaders and the managers, but they are also every one of you, every colleague, every employee.
And to paraphrase Gandhi, I would say, "Be the change that you want to see in your company."
And this requires good human qualities, and a developed emotional intelligence.
What I mean by this are such qualities as empathy, kindness, listening skills, and tolerance.
How do you develop this emotional intelligence?
You may say, "Some people are more gifted than others."
But the good news tonight is that you all have these qualities.
They are part of your human nature.
They're obstructed on a daily basis by the different stresses that surround us.
This can be physical stress - I challenge you to be kind with a dentist who is pulling one of your teeth out - emotional or mental stress.
And so, we just need to let go of this stress to rediscover and show these qualities.
Easily said, but how can we do this?
Well, there is a parallel with the emergence of mindfulness and meditation in our society.
It's no coincidence that these tools are emerging in hospitals, schools, businesses, and even at the last World Economic Forum at Davos where it was proposed to each participant to start the day with a meditation session.
I could go on and on about all the studies that show the correlation and positive impact of mindfulness on creativity and emotional intelligence.
But I'm going to suggest instead that we experience, this evening, a moment of mindfulness, together.
I ask you to welcome this exercise with the openness of mind that brought you here today and without prejudice.
It is a tool that you can use at any time of the day, on the train, in a queue, at work before a meeting, and even during a TED talk!
Are you ready?
Here we go.
Please close your eyes, sit comfortably in your seat, feel the weight of your body on your seat, your feet on the floor, the weight of your clothes on your skin.
Feel the brush of the air on your face and on your hands.
Simply notice your breathing, naturally.
Let go of all tensions, all ideas, all judgements.
Breath.
Now, turn your attention to the sounds closest to you.
and expand your awareness
to the sounds furthest away. Just relax for a few moments, here and now.
Breathe deeply, open your eyes, and reconnect with the outside world, this room, and your neighbors.
The world is changing fast.
Yesterday, in an industrial economy, we asked our head hunters to recruit manpower.
Now, in a knowledge-based economy, they are asked to recruit brains, diplomas.
I am convinced that artificial intelligence is going to give us access tomorrow to levels of knowledge that we've never had up to now.
I'm convinced that artificial intelligence is going to provide a patient with a more insightful diagnosis than that of our Doctor X.
And what we will expect from Doctor X will be his human qualities.
Because it is the human who will inspire others. It is the human who will provide new ideas. It is the human who will make the organizations and businesses of tomorrow successful.
And this will lead us to a humanistic economy where interpersonal qualities of creativity and kind-heartedness will be the selection criteria for head hunters.
Therefore, I can only encourage each and every one of you to develop and use these beautiful qualities that you possess, to practice mindfulness to your heart's content or any other tool that will allow you to reconnect to your own humanity, and to your own limitlessness.
Thank you and well done.
(Applause)
there are planets that gravitate around other stars.
They're called exoplanets.
Exoplanets, because they're outside of our solar system.
As you can imagine, it's really difficult to detect them because they're so far away from us.
And yet, regularly, astronomers announce that they have discovered new exoplanets.
There's even a recent study which suggests that of all the exoplanets that exist in our galaxy, there may be as many as 20 billion, likely to have liquid water on their surface, and thereby offering an environment potentially favourable for life.
Can you imagine?
20 billion!
So if we want to study the criteria for habitability of a planet, we will consider four criteria that must come together if the study is to be successful.
The first criterion is that the planet must be the right distance from the star.
In fact, what you're seeing on the screen is a drawing of an exoplanet.
Because they're so far away, we can't see this level of detail.
But what the artist wanted to show, was a planet within the zone of habitability of the star.
In other words, where the surface temperature would be ideal for keeping water in a liquid state for a sufficient length of time.
Closer to us, in our own solar system, there are also planets that can teach us about habitability.
But of course, today, to the best of our knowledge, there's only one that is both habitable and inhabited, which is Earth - since we're here, and there are few other candidates:
Mars, which may or may not be within the habitable zone, and then the satellites of giant planets, like Europe in orbit around Jupiter, and Enceladus, around Saturn.
There, they have tidal forces which make up for the lack of solar energy.
I'm going to talk to you about Mars, and the Curiosity mission, which recently established that in the past this planet did meet the criteria for habitability.
Curiosity landed on Mars in August 2012.
The film you're seeing here, shows its entry into the atmosphere, the descent and the landing, which in reality lasts seven minutes.
Seven minutes of terror, when the operation must be perfectly choreographed, with very little margin for error.
Everything is pre-programmed.
First a thermal shield is used, then a parachute to brake, then retro-rockets, then a system of cranes, to position this 900 kg vehicle, with precision and gentleness on the surface of Mars.
The precision of the landing is to within a few kilometers, even though it has just travelled hundreds of millions of kilometers from Earth to Mars, for nine months.
It's incredible, isn't it?
Curiosity is a NASA mission, directed by the Jet Propulsion Laboratory of the University of Caltech in California with much international collaboration.
It took five years to build.
And every day Curiosity sends us new images of Mars.
So now I'm going to show you some real photos.
Like this one.
Of course, to the uninitiated eye, all the images of Mars look alike.
But what do we see, what do you see?
We see stones, we see sand.
To put it simply, Mars is a desert.
A very dry desert, even, if we compare it with deserts on Earth.
But isn't there a contradiction with what I just told you?
That Mars was an interesting planet for a study of habitability.
That the planet is the right distance from the sun to have liquid water.
Do you see any liquid water?
It's all down to the atmosphere.
Today the atmosphere of Mars is so tenuous, that having liquid water on its surface is impossible.
We do find ice below ground, near the poles, and we might possibly find liquid water very much deeper, but on the surface, today it's a desert.
At the same time, I'm sure you've already heard in the news scientists have announced there's now proof that there was once liquid water on the surface of Mars.
Effectively, in the past, water was present.
Therefore my second criterion for habitability, after distance, is going to be time: the geological era.
We have to be in the right era, to have the right atmosphere, which provides for liquid water on the planet's surface.
Let me explain.
When planets form, in the beginning they're extremely hot,
as suggested in the drawing on your left.
In the case of our solar system, this was 4.6 billion years ago.
Then, you can imagine the planets as thermal machines which cool down over time.
So much so that at a given moment, for some of them, the temperature may be just right, and the atmosphere may be just right, to have liquid water at the surface.
That was the case for Earth and for Mars, a little over 4 billion years ago.
That's what we can see in the drawing in the middle.
And through space exploration we've accumulated, much evidence, that in fact, there used to be water on Mars.
So of course, at the beginning of space exploration in the 1960's, the myth of the Martian was busted when a desert planet was revealed.
But very soon after, during the 1970's, the images that came to us from Mars revealed canyons that looked like dried-up river beds.
And even more recently, the different missions have shown us that the minerals which form the rocks, some of these minerals were formed in the presence of water.
So we're convinced that in fact, in the distant past Mars had liquid water on its surface.
And since the planet continued to evolve with a lot of volcanic activity, its history diverged from that of Earth because it's smaller, so that finally it led to what you see in the photo on your right, which shows a planet with giant extinct volcanoes, immense canyons, and vast expanses of desert.
So why are we interested in this planet?
Well, precisely because at a moment in its history, there was water on the surface of Mars and at the same time on the surface of Earth.
And it was during this era, 3 or 4 billion years ago, that life appeared on Earth.
We know very little about things from this part of our history. but obviously we have questions to ask.
Is this phenomenon unique to Earth?
What conditions would be needed for it to be produced elsewhere?
And this is why when we study the habitability of another planet. We need to study the right era, the era where there was liquid water in its evolution, in its history.
Curiosity, as with other missions, has brought us a lot of evidence that there has been liquid water at its landing site.
And I must confess, that the first time I saw this photo, I was working in California, and we were following Martian time.
It was a rather strange experience.
The first time I saw this photo I thought it was a joke.
It could easily have been a pavement after an earthquake, something like that.
But in fact, the whole team was amazed, by this image coming from Mars which was showing us a conglomerate.
That is to say, a rock formed of fragments of rock that have been transported there, and cemented together.
And what's remarkable to the geologist's eye, is that these fragments of rock are rounded.
A little like pebbles, if you will, little pebbles that you find on a river bed.
And just by the form of these rocks, geologists are even able to calculate the amount of water that flowed by, and to say that here, there was a river with a depth of a little under one metre.
So obviously, the landing site wasn't chosen by chance.
But this image was revealing so clearly that Curiosity had landed in what had formerly been the delta of a river which had flowed there billions of years ago.
Here you are - another image, another rock photographed by Curiosity a little further away.
This flat rock was also formed in the presence of water.
In fact, there were also some like this on the first photo I showed you, the one where I mentioned the desert.
It's a sedimentary rock, which means it's formed of small fragments which were carried there by the wind or by rivers, and which, in this case, were deposited at the bottom of a lake to form this rock.
And then the water continued to flow across the fractures in the rock, as evidenced by the small distinct vein situated in the middle of the stone.
And Curiosity is able to measure the composition of these rocks, using several instruments.
For example, ChemCam, the instrument I work with, uses a laser that shoots at the rock, producing a little spark, and in simple terms, the colour of the spark tells us the chemical elements within the rock.
And so, I can tell you that the composition of the vein is different from the composition of the rock and that this vein is rich in sulphur.
It's an interesting element if I'm looking for life.
There are others, such as carbon, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus.
In fact, the composition of the rocks helps us to know the conditions in which they were formed.
And even what the environment of this region of Mars was like, when this rock was formed.
What was the temperature?
Was the water acidic?
Was the atmosphere oxidant?
What chemical elements were present?
And were they useful for life?
To reply to all these questions, I have to make use of all of Curiosity's instruments, because this forms my 3rd criterion of habitability.
It's not enough to be the right distance from the star and to be the right era to have liquid water. I also need the kind of chemical environment that's welcoming, let's say, for life.
And if possible, that it persists for quite some time, because it takes time for life to evolve.
So there we have Curiosity in the lake, long since drained of water.
We call this region the bay of Yellowknife.
It's a real photo, a selfie.
One of many. Curiosity is a little over two metres wide, it's a little bigger than me, it's equipped with ten or so instruments, of which 2 are Franco-American: ChemCam and SAM, both of which measure the composition of the rocks.
ChemCam, that's the laser I was telling you about, we can see its telescope at the top of the mast.
It's going to give us a sort of chemical survey around the robot.
And SAM is capable of carrying out very fine measurements of the composition, of a sample of rock.
So since the landing, hundreds of research scientists and engineers, take turns each day to operate, to put Curiosity to work on the surface of Mars.
At the end of each day, the robot sends all these observations to Earth via a relay satellite.
The international team snatch it all up, discuss it, and decide what to do the following day, a plan of action.
Are they going to take more measurements?
Are they going to move the robot?
Then they program the on-board computer, which will execute the program automatically the following day.
And so on.
It's a rather wonderful and quite successful example of teamwork, I'm lucky enough with a few colleagues and with help from the CNES, to participate from here in Toulouse.
Curiosity is also equipped with a small drill, a small boring machine, I'm going to zoom in on this photo, you can see the hole that has been bored into the rock, which is shown to be clay, yet another rock formed in the presence of water, and we note that the powder from this rock is of a different color, it's greyish, It's different from the color of the Martian surface, which is red.
We also see marks left by the laser in sampling the powder from the rock.
So, in bringing together all the results of all these instruments and the knowledge of the researchers involved on the project, we reached the conclusion that this region of Mars, while these rocks were forming, billions of years ago, brought together the conditions for habitability.
Namely, that there were one or more periods where water was present, maybe for tens of thousands of years, that this water was soft, pH neutral, with low salinity, and that there were chemical elements which could assist microscopic life, if it were there.
On this last point, we don't have an answer.
Habitability doesn't mean inhabited.
So we don't know, we don't have all we need to know for sure if there was life.
But we do know for sure that the environment was favourable; it was compatible.
So you have to admit now, that Mars seems a little less desert-like.
It's amazing, isn't it?
Let's see the bigger picture with this photo.
It is a photo taken by a satellite that orbits Mars, of a region a little further south than the one I just showed you, it's called 'The Kimberley'.
And Curiosity stopped there too, you can even see it in the photo, it's there.
And perhaps you can also see the tracks that the wheels have left in the sand to reach this area.
And so we continue our mission as geologists, to try to understand how planet Mars works.
And also we continue our investigations about its habitability.
Furthermore, I've told you that there was a 4th criterion, which is useful and interesting for the study of habitability.
And also, we might question why we chose to stop in this place to do some more drilling, and why not somewhere else?
But of course you now understand that the information we're looking for is recorded in the rock.
So the rock is a hard record, but in the timescales that we're considering, this information can very easily disappear.
And that's what happens on Earth, which, geologically speaking, is a very dynamic planet.
So, I have this information in my rock and I need to protect it.
And generally, this has happened by the covering of this interesting rock by another layer of rock or by sand.
But then, I then have to rediscover this information, when I'm doing my explorations.
So, either you're able to dig so deeply that what you're doing is similar to archaeology,
or you let erosion have it's way.
And that's what happened here.
The wind has blown throughout millions of years, and has revealed these mounds of bedrock, from below that are five metres high, the three mounds that you can see are the rocks which were formed billions of years ago, and which therefore help us understand what Mars was like at that time.
And so, to conclude, while you contemplate this panorama that shows us the richness of the site explored by Curiosity, I just wanted to give you a taste of the quest for habitability.
To be at the right distance from the star at the right time, to have the right environment and to have the information preserved.
If you want to take an interest in life, you will also have to allow enough time, when all conditions are favourable for life to evolve.
We're not there yet, but one entire aspect of the research work is still developing and asking these questions, it is exobiology.
I want you to realize that, on the one hand the multitude of options that all these planets offer us,
and on the other hand, the beauty
of Earth, which is habitable, all that our minds are able to uncover, and the limits of the cosmos accessible to humanity.
So you might ask me, "What's the point of all of this?"
And yes, people often ask me this, What's the point?
And I'll tell you: None at all.
That's right, because if the question is whether it will make money and change my life in the short term. No it won't.
However, do you remember the lesson given to us by Raymond Devos?
"Nothing is not nothing."
He showed how we can get something out of nothing by multiplying it. He said,
"One times nothing is nothing;
2 times nothing is not very much.
But 3 times nothing... next-to-nothing...
We can get something
with next-to-nothing, can't we?"
And research is exactly like that.
Fundamental research is about gathering such little nothings which transform our knowledge into a shared knowledge.
So of course, during a project like this one, we also improve our technology, but above all, we exercise our ability to reflect, which is our skill.
We use all our combined knowledge to understand complex phenomena.
So, ladies and gentlemen, I beg you - continue to drink your fill of curiosity.
(Applause)
Good evening
Actually, let me try that again.
(Laughter) Good evening to you all!
(Applause) Good evening, so my topic is: Taking advantage of weakness.
The topic sounds a bit pompous so I'm going to start with something very down-to-earth: a photo of my grandmother, Monique, aka Granny, actually.
My story begins two years ago, when Monique gave me a book on social entrepreneurship, a book by Muhammad Yunus.
Like many people, I loved this book for two reasons: first, with social entrepreneurship it's great not to simply maximize profits, but to solve social issues, and secondly, I loved the fact you can actually see the positive in everything he does.
That is what Muhammad does, he sees the positives in everything he describes, even capitalism.
As a result, that pushed me to try and think of ideas for responding to problems caused by capitalism.
Today, the economic system we use, it works, it is as perfect as Jessica Alba... no, I'm kidding.
Try to laugh for the jokes.
There are a few faults, a few problems, those who are forgotten in the system.
The rising inequality, environmental problems, pollution, mass unemployment.
Besides that, there are also the excessive things.
For example, there is excessive spending.
One area I found particularly excessive, is advertising.
I'll give you two seconds to read that sentence.
"Each year global spending on advertising
increases by 500 million dollars. A UN study estimates that 10% of that could eradicate world hunger." What's great about that sentence, is that it's in the film 99 Francs and it really shows the contrast between both sides of capitalism.
On one side, there is the excess, I mean the advertising budgets, budgets which are colossal.
Advertising in itself is not a bad thing.
It creates desire, promotes a product.
That's not unhealthy in itself.
Nonetheless, it is an excessive budget.
The other part of the sentence really shows the cracks in capitalism, which are never actually filled.
The North-South inequality, for example.
We're finally noticing, that of this phenomenal budget, less than half would be enough to eradicate world hunger.
That shows a real gap between the two.
I asked myself: why don't we stop seeing them as opposites but try to join them together?
To create a tool which would allow us, a bit like Robin Hood, to create a link to use some of the excessive advertising spending, to fill one of these gaps.
I started to think, etc.
In the end, I had an idea.
It came at a slightly unexpected moment, while I was in the shower.
There are two places for thinking, in the shower and on the toilet.
For me, it was more in the shower.
I got this idea, I was really happy.
Today this idea has been turned into a start-up called Goodeed.
We're currently raising funds, today, there are 4 of us.
Thank you.
(Applause) Tristan and Thomas, who are in the audience.
Actually, Thomas couldn't come due to car trouble.
Tristan is Goodeed's web designer, he is in the audience.
So what is this really cool idea?
It is a website where you can make free donations.
You go onto the website, You choose a donation, a vaccine, a tree, or a meal.
Then you watch an advertisement.
The money generated by the ad funds the donation.
It's a free donation for internet users.
That's the first side.
The second, not for the user, but for the advertiser, which I want to go into this evening, is showing that what is excessive in capitalism, spending which is seen as excessive, ultimately as something negative, is now re-humanised.
It gives new meaning to ads.
It allows advertising budgets to be meaningful and useful again.
Today, Goodeed has enabled funding with the World Food Programme in Kenya, meals for 18,000 children in a month.
And that's thanks to your donations more than 500,000 of them, and thanks to advertising.
Ultimately, what can be seen as negative, can also be positive.
We just need to create a tool, try and be innovative to transform it into something positive.
The Chinese have been doing it for millennia.
It's in their vocabulary.
The Chinese for "crisis" is "Weiji".
"Wei", which is "danger".
The first symbol is a man threatening someone with a knife.
It doesn't look it, but that's what it is.
The second character is
opportunity, chance. It's "Ji".
It shows that in the most critical situations, you can still bounce back.
It is seeing positive in the negative.
When a situation upsets us, we will be spurred to see things differently, in a new way.
I came to say this to you this evening: try and see the fixed things, like advertising, it's certainly an excessive expense, a negative, and there are faults with capitalism.
We can can see them differently and try to creatively make links.
So that's it, build businesses that have that social aspect in their DNA.
Goodnight, and thank you so much.
(Applause)
According to the World Health Organization 100 million litres of blood is needed worldwide to satisfy the world population's needs.
Moreover, the French Blood Service has stated that 90% of French people know that donating blood saves lives.
But despite this, only 4% do it each year.
And this is true for most industrialized nations.
Given the shortfall between the amount of blood donated and the needs of the global population, we need to find another way in order to respond to this real public health problem.
As surprising as this may seem, I might have found one solution.
And I found that solution on a beach in Brittany.
Even as a little boy, I was fascinated by the ocean, and I think those television programs by Jacques Cousteau had something to do with it.
So obviously, I decided that I would work in that field, and I became a doctor in marine biology.
One particular environment quickly caught my attention as it was colonised by very old organisms.
It was the foreshore, a scientific name for an environment that you surely like as it's the beach.
The high tide covers Brittany's beaches twice daily.
And the sand on these beaches shelters some very old organisms which you've probably noticed by the trails that these organisms leave on the sand when you set down your towel.
In fact, these trails show the presence of a marine organism which is called the lugworm.
So, lugworm is the name of a sea worm common on beaches in Brittany known locally as Buzuc.
So I studied this sea worm for answers about respiratory ecophysiology.
So what does that mean?
It's simple really, I was interested in this worm's breathing.
I was trying to understand how this worm breathed between high and low tides.
In order to answer that burning research question, (Laughter) I took an interest in the animal's blood.
Actually, blood is an extremely interesting biological fluid.
It is the interface between an organism's physiology and its environment.
In fact, blood is made up of different cells but the molecule that transports oxygen, oxygen that is vital to all living organisms, which is a bit like - if I can use a mechanical analogy - oxygen is a bit like the fuel that you put in your car.
Without fuel, the car stalls.
And without oxygen, death is certain.
Actually, blood contains specific cells called red blood cells.
Red blood cells are like a small car which take gas to your body's cells.
And more accurately, this molecule contains a protein called hemoglobin.
Hemoglobin is a molecule that can bind oxygen.
So imagine my surprise, when the blood of this here seaworm didn't contain any red blood cells.
To be honest, at first, I didn't understand the magnitude of this study.
But my discovery became known to a research group called the Red Blood Cell Club.
(Laughter) Thus, I was invited to a Parisian hospital to present my research in front of a panel of doctors, haemotologists.
And at the end of my scientific conference several of them came down the ampitheatre and asked me the following questions, "But Sir, haven't you found the molecule with that structure, with that function?"
"Well, yes I have!"
"We've been searching for that molecule for over 40 years to make a universal blood substitute!"
You and I, we have the ABO blood type, rhesus positive or rhesus negative.
Only O negative is the universal donor type.
The absence of red blood cells in that animal would make that molecule universal.
Going back to the lab to test that theory, I rushed off to the beach to collect a few hundred lugworms, merely in an attempt to collect the hemoglobin present in their circulatory system. After purifying this molecule using traditional lab techniques I was eager to perform transfusions on rodents.
Imagine my surprise when after removing more than 80% of their blood in a lab, I did a molecular transfusion on these animals and nothing happened.
(Laughter) The organisms, these rodents, living with the hemoglobin of sea worms.
A surprising discovery, offering medicine tremendous hope.
Thumbing its nose at all those skeptics who asked me, "What is the point of studying how sea worms breathe?
(Laughter) Don't you have anything else to do in a CNRS lab?"
(Laughter) In order to further develop this research, I am forced to leave the CNRS to create a biotechnology company that will develop these molecules for medical use.
And only a few hundred grams of lugworms are needed to make one bag of this globular type.
There are many uses for this molecule.
Why?
Simply because oxygen is central to all biological and physiological processes so, ultimately, to life.
I spent the first years after starting this company, developing an industrial manufacturing process for my sea worms.
As a biologist, it was not an option for me to remove them from every beach in Brittany.
And today, these worms are made using aquaculture in a totally controlled and traceable environment.
Hundreds of tonnes of this animal are made using aquaculture.
Apart from the worm, the main issue was the biomass. We had to find an industrial production system to extract these molecules in pharmaceutical conditions.
And today, we actually have a whole process which allows us to extract the biomass molecules.
This industrial process and the production of sea worms provides a multitude of uses.
And I'm going to mention three although there are lots.
First, there's blood transfusion.
You know, when you give blood, a bag of blood can be stored for 42 days, because red blood cells are perishable.
Moreover, the cold chain must be kept at 4 °C.
Just to remind you that this molecule is not contained in red blood cells.
And so it is possible to get freeze-dried blood, by which I mean powdered blood, which can be put back into solution thanks to pharmaceutical water.
So no more storage problem.
No more 4 °C preservation problem.
This product could be readily available for an emergency, natural disaster, wherever a patient urgently needs a blood transfusion.
Today, this product is in development thanks to a partnership with the U.S. Army.
The second use is healing.
We're not talking about just any type of wound.
Wounds found in people who suffer from diabetes, known as Diabetic Foot Syndrome, people who suffer from pressure sores, large burns, all of these wounds have difficulty healing themselves.
Why?
Well simply because of bad blood circulation.
And unfortunately, the wounds found in people who suffer from diabetes generally end badly as most have to be amputated.
And this affects 20 million people across the globe.
We have been able to show that bandages soaked with this molecule were able to deliver oxygen to the feet, and to these wounds, ultimately avoiding amputation.
The third use, which is closest to completion today as a human trial will take place at the end of the year, is organ transplantation.
In France, 500 people die each year because of a shortage of organs on a waiting list of 19,000 patients.
Why?
Because actually, the solutions used in clinics today are made up of just water and salt but nothing to carry oxygen.
When an organ is removed from a donor, it is immediately disconnected from blood circulation.
And we have been able to show that by using this molecule, it is possible to considerably increase the time an organ can be preserved.
For a heart today, you have 4 hours between removal from the donor and the moment it is inserted into the recipient.
For a kidney, it's 12 hours.
With this molecule, today, we have been able to double the time for preserving these organs and preserve a kidney for four times as long.
So today, we are able to increase the pool of organs available for transplant.
Research is progressing, but it is not progressing as quickly as we would like.
Why?
Because the drug cycle is long, very long, very, very long, and while waiting for our product to be put on the market, which could save millions of lives around the world, I can only urge you to go and give blood.
Be generous in order to save lives.
And a little advice, between friends: go quickly, because tomorrow, it may be an act of the past.
Thank you.
(Applause)
I just got back from Agadez, Niger.
Agadez, maybe some of you know it, used to be the jewel of Sahara, the entry point for the desert, the major point of the Dakar Rally.
There are no more tourists since 2010's kidnappings.
However, there are migrants, hundreds and hundreds of migrants coming from West Africa.
The mayor told me, "During the most favorable season for migration, the population triples."
Within two weeks when it gets less hot.
39°C instead of 45.
For those who cross the Sahara in the back of a pick-up truck heading for Libya, it matters.
You might tell me, "Not another migrants story, that's all we keep hearing about."
But what if I told you that no one is speaking about it?
We only hear about the refugees.
The ones you have been shown on television are Syrians, Iraqis,
running away from war.
We have been nicely explained that they are doctors, lawyers, that they have a big house, a domestic servant back home.
They are a bit like us, they are white.
I report about Africa for a magazine called Le Point.
And the people I started to follow since June are those who are unwanted here.
They are poor, not quite graduated, they are black.
They will never get the status of refugee.
They will always be stereotyped as asylum seekers on the move.
While Syrians take a few weeks to reach Europe, they usually spend many years.
Many of them are stuck in Libya.
Some of them get murdered for no reason.
Many of them die on the way, in the Sahara.
The desert is scattered with corpses.
The idea came to me back in April: I was queuing at an after-sales service for my computer.
A nice retired lady sat next to me, looking for conversation.
She asked me what was my job.
So I told her, "Reporter in Africa."
She told me, "Poor thing, that's got to be tough."
I told her, "Well, I like it.
I do not understand why these people come here.
There are no jobs for them.
They are coming for the benefits, right?
Then they sleep on my landing and smell bad."
So I answered her, "I know where they come from and you would do the same thing."
My ticket number came out at last so I stood, with dignity, then I wondered: do we truly know why these people leave?
Those who are not running away from war.
Is this really a better place?
So I searched for a country with lots of people leaving and that would not be at war.
It was not very difficult as the International Organization for Migration had just released a report, and the country with the greatest number of nationals in absolute value who had tried to cross the Mediterranean sea between January and March 2015 was Gambia.
More than Syria, more than Nigeria.
There are 175 million inhabitants in Nigeria.
In Gambia: 1.9.
A very small country.
People ran for their lives.
I wanted to understand.
Of course, there were some hints: a dictator who came to power with a coup d'état in 1994, Yaya Jammeh, who pretends he can cure AIDS thanks to a drink made of plants and verses from the Koran, who get his opponents eliminated, if not shot in public.
There were also economic indicators: 1,700 dollars of GDP per capita, which makes it the 210th country in 230.
Human development.
They are 172nd out of 187.
Long story short, misery.
Once I was there, I realized it was even more complicated.
It always happens like this.
You always find out on the spot.
It was a combination of poverty, ignorance, hope, social pressure that kept young people leaving.
And absolutely nothing could discourage them.
This is why I followed their path, I went to Agadez, the migration transit hub.
And this is why this evening I want to tell you about everything we think we know about migrants that is absolutely false.
First misconception: passing through is expensive; with all this money, couldn't they do something else?
Create a company?
Well they don't.
Because they don't leave with the amount required for their trip, they don't have it.
They work on the road.
For instance, Jamal Barry, 25. I met him in Gambia, near Serekunda.
Jamal builds furniture.
When I met him, his last order dated back to one month ago: two armchairs, one double sofa, one triple sofa.
Paid 450 dalasis by his boss.
9 euros for 12 working days.
Jamal's parents died, he has four brothers and sisters, he wanted to send money from Europe, and then, as many others, he had to stop in Libya.
He had no money left.
He was extorted at the checkpoint of each country he went through.
Senegal, Mali, Burkina, Niger, Libya.
Then he was kidnapped.
Then he became sick.
So he went back after 8 months.
He still drew me the truck on which the Tuareg carry the migrants throughout the Sahara.
As you can see, those are cages fitted out to stock as much as possible.
He was sitting at the end of a beam.
He had to hold on to avoid falling out as the truck would not stop.
At the beginning of the ride
they were all packed. Then fewer and fewer, as they threw away in the desert the corpses of those who died from dehydration.
He told me, "Each day, I will go back because here I am already dead."
Second misconception.
They are disloyal.
They leave the country who needs these good workers.
It is the exact opposite: they leave to help their families.
In Africa there is no such thing as pension contributions.
Children assure their own parents' old days.
Let's look at the case of this man, Balamin Jaiteh.
The picture he is holding in his hands is the one of his son, Yankuba.
Yankuba was 23 years old when he attempted to take the trip, he also thought he would reach Europe, he also had to stop at Sebha, in Libya.
And was unfortunate.
Libyans were looking for an African man from his ghetto.
Those are the houses migrants are crammed in before being able to carry on.
He told them he did not know where he was.
They answered, "You are lying, you black people all know each other."
They soaked him with gasoline.
They struck a match.
Yankuba died burned alive.
It took days to his father before he would speak to me. He felt guilty.
He told me, "I had been doing this since 1975.
I have worked in Mali, in Burkina-Faso, in Gabon, in Côte d'Ivoire, in Niger and in Libya.
Helping your old parents is normal, by the way, any time he could work he would send money to us - you see, we could restore the house."
His wife was staring at the floor.
One of his daughters had left to hide and cry.
When I asked Balamin, "Have you forbidden your children to leave?
Have you told them it was dangerous?"
He told me, "Not clearly."
At the moment, it is a source of income they can't deprive themselves from.
Third misconception.
They are not that poor, they have cellphones.
So they do have cellphones, sometimes that is all they have.
No electricity, no running water, but smartphones.
Not the latest things, only bootlegs that spend hours to recharge, hours to load a web page.
Because the most reputable smuggler, the most deceiving, is not the starving guy from Agadez who crams migrants in the back of his pick-up car.
Actually, it is the internet.
It is the social networks.
They spend hours dreaming looking at the pictures of those who have already reached Europe, and dreaming that someday they will also manage to pass through.
Fourth misconception.
They all will swarm into France to get family allowances.
No, and I know this might seem offensive, but no one mentioned France to me.
At the bus station of Niamey, the capital city of Niger, I spoke to a Malian who insisted on speaking English, as his boss was Nigerian, which means English-speaking, and he wanted to practice his English.
He had Europe in mind, but not France at all.
England, or especially, Germany.
Even the Senegalese from the ghettos of Agadez, dream of Germany, and do not even know nobody speaks French there.
As for the benefits, no one is aware of them.
Let's briefly interest ourselves in Kenya.
Here is Farhiyo Salah, 22 years old.
Farhiyo grew up in the biggest refugee camp in the world, at the frontier with Somalia, it is called Dadaab.
Today, there are 350,000 people.
When I met her back in July, she had been just granted a scholarship to study in Canada.
She told me, "All my life I have received help from NGOs, now I want my own job, I want to earn my own money, to become independent.
Then I will come back, and change women's condition in Africa."
Farhiyo wants to become a diplomat or a gynecologist, not to have eight children all taken care by the Canadian governement.
Lastly, fifth misconception: there are many issues back there, they will always dream of Europe.
It's hopeless.
Yes and no.
Europe is this place brothers write about saying, "Just come, there is plenty of job here." But for most of those I spoke with, if they had had a choice, they would have done as the previous generations: they would have migrated within Africa, and more specifically in Libya.
The first time Ousmane Sawo, 28 years old, went to Libya, it was in 2008.
He stayed for 2 years and a half.
He was a mason.
He earned around 200 euros per month.
He had got his house built, in Gambia.
It had become too dangerous, one of his friends had died before him.
He went back home.
In 2013, he had no money left at all.
He thought he would do as everyone else and try to go to Italy.
Instead of a boat, he found himself in jail for 6 months in Tripoli, caught in a scam of his smuggler.
Ousmane, nowadays, earns in Gambia, when he is able to find some work, 4 euros.
Only for his children's schooling and food, he spends 3.
He told me, "Only by making tea at home I go over my budget.
Everyday God makes, I pray for my children not to become sick, as I wouldn't afford to have them cured."
As the Senegalese from Agadez told me, "We have to pass across, because things don't go well in Libya."
They told me, 'The worst thing is to die poor.
So we don't have a choice."
Even if they are scared, even though they have seen the shipwrecks on France 24.
They told me, "Dying is nothing, we are trying our luck."
This is why closing our borders will always be pointless.
Because as long as these young Africans will have no hope for a better life, or even a life, in their country, they will keep coming.
And as you can see, we would do the same thing as well.
Thank you.
(Applause)
